<div class="post-date">Sep 22</div>
<h2><a https://yarnetsky.github.io/ontheriversedge/index.html?id=974" title="My evening in the children&#8217;s room"> My evening in the children&#8217;s room</a></h2>

<div class="entry">


     

  	<p>I worked tonight instead of my usual Wednesday as the children&#8217;s librarian went to a conference today.</p>

	<p>I helped some high school students with a project that seemed a little too broad (just about everything under the sun dealing with the turn of the 19th to 20th century from Mother Jones to inventions). I also shelved some books.</p>

	<p>I&#8217;m always amazed how many cool children&#8217;s books there are in our library. I have no idea if the kids think they&#8217;re cool, but I do.</p>

	<p>Tonight I read easy readers about a Chinese girl celebrating the Fourth of July, a boy whose robot goes crazy when he should be in bed sleeping, a Jewish girl preparing for the sabbath dinner with her grandmother, about a young girl in Jim Crow Nashville discoving the library (the only integrated place in the city practically), and one illustrating blues lyrics.</p>

	<p>The latter two books were eye reopening. Certainly, I&#8217;ve read about what life was like under segregation. But the living the easy life of small-town America 2004, you forget the pain that was suffered. I never realized that Billie Holiday&#8217;s &#8220;Strange Fruit&#8221; referred to lynchings. I never heard the lyrics.</p>

	<p>After reading a children&#8217;s book (a children&#8217;s book!!!!), it leaves one wondering how one could ever forget.</p>

	<p>&#8220;Southern trees bear strange fruit,<br />
Blood on the leaves and blood at the root,<br />
Black bodies swinging in the southern breeze,<br />
Strange fruit hanging from the poplar trees.&#8221; </p>



 
<div class="line"></div>

<div class="smallcat">Posted in <a https://yarnetsky.github.io/ontheriversedge/index.html?c=Library">Library</a></div>
<div class="smalluser"> by <a https://yarnetsky.github.io/ontheriversedge/index.html?author=E.G.+Yarnetsky">E.G. Yarnetsky</a></div>
