<div class="post-date">Jul 23</div>
<h2><a https://yarnetsky.github.io/ontheriversedge/index.html?id=938" title="Fair was a success"> Fair was a success</a></h2>

<div class="entry">


     

  	<p>We survived the Jefferson County 4-H Fair in one piece. Other than needing to get the talking points out to everyone things worked rather well for our first time out.</p>

	<p>The biggest hit was our Accu-Cut puzzles. We printed out 4 per page flyers that said &#8220;Puzzled? Come to the Library for Answers.&#8221; We used that as a talking point with the kids and parents. We then had them drawing pictures on the back. I hammed it up with the kids. I had them say magical words &#8220;ugily, buggily, boo!&#8221; and roled the puzzle through the cutter &#8220;and poof, you have a puzzle.&#8221;</p>

	<p>However, I suspect that free-form drawing is becoming a lost art as a number of kids were dumbstruck with the concept. I continued hamming it up and made suggestions to get their brains going. &#8220;You can draw cars, balloons, sheep, horses, hearts&#8230; hey, you could even draw me!&#8221; pregnent pause. &#8220;No? I guess not.&#8221; They&#8217;d laugh and start drawing something. However, a mother-daughter combo actually took me up on the joke. That was even funnier.</p>

	<p>A few days later, Darlene ran into a mother who said her kids were <b>still</b> playing with the puzzles and were even making up games to play with them. So while kids drawing may be a lost art, creativity is not!</p>

	<p>I think we managed to have 300 folks doing puzzles over the week.</p>

	<p>Our drawing for free books and CDs was a general success as well. We drew 42 winners from more than 340 entries. About half of the winners had picked up their prizes when I left for Ohio yesterday.</p>

	<p>For prizes we used the duplicate CDs from the &#8220;CD price-fixing&#8221; settlement shipment we received earlier this summer. We also used a small number of the books donated to the library that we didn&#8217;t add to the collection.</p>

	<p>It was fun.</p>



 
<div class="line"></div>

